{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 13:14:37.042046", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnostic Report\nSummary\n- Control plane (BGP) is converged and stable across the FRR routers: all expected BGP adjacencies are established and prefixes are being exchanged.\n- Data-plane reachability tests are mixed: pc_0_0 can reach its leaf; pc_0_1 could not be inspected (container/host not running). Routing tables on leaves/spines indicate reachability for the advertised /24 host subnets across the fabric.\n- Primary anomaly: one host (pc_0_1) and some test tooling were unavailable (container not running). This appears to be an environment/host-level failure rather than a routing protocol failure.\n\nScope of checks performed\n- Queried network configuration (ifconfig / ip addr / routes) for hosts and routers where available.\n- Queried FRR BGP summaries and BGP tables (show ip bgp summary / show ip bgp).\n- Performed a ping from pc_0_0 to its leaf router.\n- Attempted other reachability checks; some failed due to the target container/device not running.\n\nFindings (detailed)\n\n1) BGP control plane — healthy\n- All FRR routers show established BGP neighbors and routes exchanged.\n  - leaf_router_0_0: 4 neighbors, each Neighbor State shows prefixes received (PfxRcd = 7 for super/spine peers), BGP adjacencies Up.\n  - leaf_router_0_1: 4 neighbors, BGP adjacencies Up.\n  - spine_router_0_0 and spine_router_0_1: each show neighbors to the super-spine(s) and leaves with prefixes received; PfxRcd counts consistent with topology.\n  - super_spine_router_0: shows neighbors to all spines, each with prefixes received.\n- BGP route tables on leaves show the local /24 installed as local (0.0.0.0 next-hop) and remote /24s learned via spine nexthops. Example:\n  - leaf_router_0_0 show ip bgp: 10.0.0.0/24 is local; 10.0.1/2/3/ and 10.1.* learned with valid AS-PATHs and next-hops (multiple paths present).\n- No BGP sessions in Active/Idle or with high InQ/OutQ; no obvious BGP flaps in the sampled outputs.\n\n2) Data plane — mostly consistent, limited by unavailable host\n- pc_0_0:\n  - ip 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1 (leaf_router_0_0).\n  - Ping from pc_0_0 to leaf_router_0_0 (172.16.0.33) succeeded: 0% loss, rtt avg ~0.81 ms. This verifies at least local host-to-leaf data-plane connectivity.\n- pc_0_1:\n  - Attempts to retrieve pc_0_1 network config failed due to the container not running (tool returned: container is not running). Thus its state could not be verified.\n- Leaf routers have /24 interfaces configured for hosts (eth4 on leaves: 10.0.0.1 and 10.0.1.1), and their routing tables contain routes for other pod host subnets with valid BGP next-hops (evidence of end-to-end routing knowledge).\n\n3) Host / environment anomalies\n- Several tool operations failed referencing a container not running:\n  - get_reachability failed initially with: \"container ... is not running\".\n  - get_host_net_config for pc_0_1 failed with the same container-not-running error.\n  - ping_pair attempts to some IPs returned \"Device ... is not running\".\n- This indicates at least one host container (pc_0_1) is down/unavailable in the lab environment. That prevents full end-to-end reachability verification between hosts.\n\nLocalization of faulty devices/components\n- pc_0_1 (host) — likely down/unavailable. Evidence:\n  - get_host_net_config against pc_0_1 returned a docker/container-not-running error.\n  - No ip/ifconfig output available for pc_0_1.\n- Test tooling / environment: some reachability tools failed because a container involved in the test harness is not running (this may be the same container as pc_0_1 or another environment container). Evidence: explicit \"container ... is not running\" errors from the tool calls.\n- No router-level fault detected in the FRR routing instances sampled (leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1, spine_router_0_0, spine_router_0_1, super_spine_router_0 all responded to config and BGP queries and show adjacencies and routes).\n\nEvidence (selected outputs / observations)\n- pc_0_0 ifconfig and route:\n  - eth0: inet 10.0.0.2/24, default via 10.0.0.1\n- Ping from pc_0_0 to leaf_router_0_0:\n  - 4 packets transmitted, 4 received, rtt avg 0.807 ms.\n- leaf_router_0_0 ifconfig and ip route:\n  - eth4: 10.0.0.1/24\n  - Routes: 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.40 (BGP), 10.1.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.32 (BGP), etc.\n- BGP summaries:\n  - leaf_router_0_0: 4 neighbors, all Up, Peer PfxRcd counts present.\n  - leaf_router_0_1: 4 neighbors, all Up.\n  - spine_router_0_0 / spine_router_0_1 / super_spine_router_0: all neighbors Up with prefixes exchanged.\n- BGP table excerpts:\n  - leaf_router_0_0 shows 10.0.0.0/24 local (0.0.0.0 next-hop) and other 10.0.X/24 and 10.1.X/24 networks learned with expected AS-PATHs and next-hops.\n  - leaf_router_0_1 shows 10.0.1.0/24 local and remote subnets learned.\n\nRoot-cause assessment (most likely)\n- Primary root cause for inability to fully validate host-to-host connectivity: pc_0_1 (or a lab container providing that host) is not running/unavailable. This is an environment/host-level failure preventing data-plane verification on that host.\n- No evidence of routing protocol misbehavior or BGP convergence problems in the inspected routers. The control plane appears healthy and consistent with the topology.\n\nNotes and caveats\n- Some tool failures (container-not-running) limit the completeness of data-plane testing — specifically, we could not run reachability tests involving pc_0_1 nor could we use the get_reachability tool that aggregates ping results.\n- The BGP outputs were sampled from several routers and indicate convergence at the time of capture, but continuous monitoring would be required to rule out transient flaps not captured here.\n- Counters/snapshots are point-in-time; some interface packet counters (e.g., leaf eth4 showing zeros) may reflect timing differences between captures and tests.\n\nConclusion\n- Control-plane: OK. BGP adjacencies established;